      <article class="post-content">

        <div class="snippet-answer">
          <p>In local SEO, an <strong>entity</strong> is a clearly defined business or place that Google identifies and catalogs in its Knowledge Graph. Entity strength — built through consistent NAP data, <code>LocalBusiness</code> schema markup, and a complete Google Business Profile — directly determines <strong>local pack visibility, knowledge panel presence, and map rankings</strong>.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="term-meta-strip">
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Results timeline</div>
            <div class="tms-value">3–6 months</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Category</div>
            <div class="tms-value">Local SEO</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Primary signal</div>
            <div class="tms-value">NAP consistency</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Difficulty</div>
            <div class="tms-value">Intermediate</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <p class="lede-p">Local SEO is fundamentally about entity clarity. Google doesn't rank pages in the local pack — it ranks business entities. The clearer and more consistent your entity signals are across Google Business Profile, schema markup, and citations, the higher you rank in proximity searches.</p>

        <h2 id="what-is">What is an entity in local SEO?</h2>
        <p>An entity in local SEO is a business or place that Google recognizes as a distinct, verified object in its Knowledge Graph. Unlike a general entity (which can be any concept), a local business entity has specific attributes Google uses for proximity ranking:</p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Name</strong> — the exact business name as it appears in the real world</li>
          <li><strong>Address</strong> — a specific physical location Google can geocode</li>
          <li><strong>Phone number</strong> — a local number tied to that address</li>
          <li><strong>Category</strong> — what type of business it is (plumber, dentist, restaurant)</li>
          <li><strong>Service area</strong> — which geographic radius the business serves</li>
          <li><strong>Reviews</strong> — social proof signals reinforcing entity trustworthiness</li>
        </ul>
        <p>When these signals are consistent and reinforced across multiple authoritative sources, Google confidently includes the entity in local pack results for relevant proximity queries.</p>

        <div class="callout callout-info">
          <div class="callout-label">Why consistency is the core signal</div>
          <p>Google cross-references your business name, address, and phone number (NAP) across dozens of sources — your website, GBP, Yelp, Bing Places, industry directories. <strong>Any inconsistency creates entity ambiguity</strong>, and ambiguous entities rank lower because Google is less confident they're the correct result.</p>
        </div>

        <h2 id="why-it-matters">Why entity strength matters for local rankings</h2>
        <p>Local pack rankings (the 3-pack shown above organic results) are dominated by entities with high clarity. Five reasons entity strength is the leverage point in local SEO:</p>
        <ol>
          <li><strong>Direct visibility in the local pack.</strong> Google ranks entities, not websites, in the 3-pack. A business without strong entity signals doesn't appear regardless of website quality.</li>
          <li><strong>Knowledge panel presence.</strong> Recognized entities with sufficient authority earn knowledge panels for branded searches — free real estate at the top of search results.</li>
          <li><strong>Proximity ranking weight.</strong> Google's proximity algorithm rewards entity clarity. A business 2 miles from the searcher with strong entity signals beats a competitor 0.5 miles away with inconsistent signals.</li>
          <li><strong>Citation authority compounds.</strong> Each new citation mentioning your consistent NAP reinforces the entity signal, with compounding returns over time — unlike paid ads that stop the moment the budget runs out.</li>
          <li><strong>Review signals attach to the entity.</strong> Google Reviews are associated with your business entity, not just your GBP listing. Strong review signals lift the entity's trust score across all local ranking factors.</li>
        </ol>

        <h2 id="how-it-works">How Google builds local entity understanding</h2>
        <p>Google assembles entity signals from multiple sources and cross-references them to establish confidence:</p>
        <p><strong>Google Business Profile:</strong> The most direct entity declaration. Name, category, address, hours, photos, and reviews feed directly into the local ranking algorithm.</p>
        <p><strong>Website schema markup:</strong> <code>LocalBusiness</code> schema on your website makes the entity machine-readable, adding geo-coordinates, service offerings, and opening hours that GBP alone may not capture.</p>
        <p><strong>Citations:</strong> Mentions of your NAP on directories (Yelp, YP, Bing Places, industry-specific directories) act as third-party confirmations of the entity's existence and location.</p>
        <p><strong>Brand mentions:</strong> Even without a link, mentions of your business name on authoritative local sites (local news, chambers of commerce, local blogs) strengthen entity recognition.</p>

        <h2 id="types">Local entity vs. national brand entity — differences that matter</h2>

        <div class="table-wrap">
